description.title.name: Name
description.title.deploymentHighlightsTe: Channels point to repositories where Kubernetes resources are stored, such as Git, Helm chart, or object storage repositories, or Namespaces on the local cluster. Channels support multiple subscriptions from multiple targets.

Each channel has certain gate conditions that a resource channel has to meet in order to get deployed to such channel. If the resource is missing all the required conditions, it will initially shown as "pending" until more resource conditions are added.
Deployables are Kubernetes resources that contain templates that wrap other Kubernetes resources to be deployed. They are also used to represent Helm charts.
Resource conditions can be added manually or automated based on events outcome. When a resource has all the conditions that a channel gate requires, it will then be deployed to such channel.
Placement rules define the target clusters where subscriptions are delivered. This is done by cluster name, cluster resource annotation(s), or cluster resource label(s).
Subscriptions identify Kubernetes resources within channels (source repositories). Then, the subscription places the Kubernetes resources on the target clusters.

welcome.paragraph.mcm.title: Multicluster operations and visibility
welcome.paragraph.mcm.description: IBM Multicloud Manager provides a way to perform parallel queries against multiple clusters and aggregate that information by various criteria. This information is augmented by near real-time pod traffic views, using WeaveScope, which enables an understanding of how pods inter-communicate. Using the IBM Multicloud Manager, you can have rich views of how clusters operate within the environment. You can see dashboards of aggregated information across multiple clusters, view the topology of resources within those clusters, or navigate into individual clusters consoles for more detailed views.

welcome.paragraph.example.description: View the health of all the clusters in a given region. Know how many nodes are down in all the clusters. View the pods in a given namespace in all development clusters. See all the failed pods in a specific data center.
